`crates/steno/` is the compiler-and-tooling crate that turns `.steno` theory source into Plover dictionaries, LSP/nvim snippets, and editor-behavior-aware output, plus the integration tests that pin its behavior against a real corpus (`dict.steno`) and a headless Neovim instance. Depending on this crate at the top gets you `lib.rs`'s re-exports and the binaries in `src/bin/`; the tests are the enforceable contract for everything downstream of the pipeline stages.

The crate is organized as one staged, one-directional pipeline (`parse` → `expand` → `render`/`snippet`) with two cross-cutting engines (`stroke/`, `editor/`) and one shared serializer (`json_out.rs`) that all output paths must funnel through to preserve byte-for-byte JSON compatibility. The test suite mirrors this staging file-by-file but adds a load-bearing coupling the source tree itself doesn't have: nine of eleven integration-test files hardcode specific strokes and counts from the repo-root `dict.steno`, so corpus edits and test edits must land together, and any stroke the corpus repurposes (e.g. `STKWR-LT`) needs a hand-built `TypedEntry` fixture as the established escape hatch.

Two invariants span both `src/` and `tests/`: the `PLAIN`/`SMART` editor-profile semantics silently change output in both `render/` and `blocks.rs` with no compiler-enforced link between them (tests catch this only where fixtures exist), and the "terminal"-flag classification from `expand/family.rs` governs both rendering completeness and snippet sentinel-wrapping — `snippet.rs`'s prefix-collision test and `nvim_plugin.rs`'s live-editor test both depend on this rule holding, one statically and one behaviorally. Across the whole crate, expected-failure conditions surface as typed errors (`error.rs`) rather than panics, except in the test helpers themselves, which routinely `.unwrap()` over real corpus data and turn parse/lookup failures into bare panics rather than assertions.

No `intent.md` is present for this directory, so no divergence check applies.